</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3351FA8FFC6B15A30D078B2B19EF48B" pageId="8" pageNumber="49" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8B904C23FFC6B15A30D078B2B19EF48B" blockId="8.[151,1437,151,752]" pageId="8" pageNumber="49">
<emphasis id="B95B9031FFC6B15A30D078B2B23BF4B6" bold="true" box="[199,334,692,717]" pageId="8" pageNumber="49">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet is derived from the Latin 
<emphasis id="B95B9031FFC6B15A339978B3B0A7F4B7" box="[910,978,693,716]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="49">rectus</emphasis>
(straight), referring to the uncus with posterior margin nearly straight in the male genitalia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
